title: Grateful Dead Live at Nassau Coliseum on 1991-03-29
description: Feel Like A Stranger, Sugaree, Walkin' Blues, Dire Wolf, Me & My Uncle-> Mexicali Blues, Althea, When I Paint My Masterpiece Iko Iko, Saint Of Circumstance, New Speedway Boogie-> Truckin'-> Drums-> Jam-> The Other One-> Wharf Rat-> Throwing Stones-> Touch Of Gray, E: Brokedown Palace

reviews.review_text: decent night My 50th show and I had floor seets at the coliseum.  Excellent first set marred by an unexplained PA outage.  You can't hear it on the download but during Masterpiece the sound went out, then came back on, completely.  It is then you realize how loud they are, like being in an airplane engine.  They shortenend the set, I felt a little gipped out of a Bird Song, although my friend says the would have finished with the New Speedway they played in II.  Over all a good show, the NSB>Truckin' was nice.  Indicative of the tour, not great, didn't suck.  3.5 stars....go to 4 because the sound on the board is pretty good.

3/29/91 PA problems forced the end of the first set after Masterpiece. No Hornsby this run. 

Very good sound (5 stars), 3 star performance, second set is not that well played IMHO.
i love it what a great sounding recording.  I remember listening to this on "tape" in college all the time.  This sounds better than the version I had then.  The Sugaree is great.

shake it SBDS . . . ugh. I would love to see a nice FOB of this show posted. This one suffers from way too much Wince in the right channel. The Sugaree is the standout of this show, IMO. I remember hitting the floor when the right PA tower shorted out during Masterpiece. A classic "WTF?" momnet.

3-29-91 10th Row Center Floor Seat This was the closest I ever got with a reserved seat, and it was a totally different experience from all previous shows, being under the stage lights was like being in a virtual living room with the band.  All the band members were smiling, and everyone seemed to be in a good mood, and the band played well, but the technical difficulties due to the rain water leaking in put a damper on things.   Listen to the crowd roar when Vince hits his first few notes of Stranger. This was a new-sounding Dead.  This SBD is marred by the short-circuiting during the 1st set.
amps i had good seats for all three nites thanx to mail order tix when the speakers exploded well it sounded like a M100 IN MY state of liqifryed mind all three nites smoked

Sugaree This site has afforded me the opportunity to listen to so many shows.  What I have found is that post-Brent, 2 songs in particular just went to a whole new level.  Wharf Rat is one that comes to mind.  The other is Sugaree.  Of course Lake Placid is the mother of all, but this one in particular is absolutely smoking.  Jesus, I was at this show and don't remember it being this good.  You can hear Jerry commenting afterwards that this one "had a little life to it."  The BEST of 1991 (although 6/25 is a CH away)...by far.

unlocking the memories Wow nice well-balanced soundboard!  Thanks to all for allowing me to re-live so many moments that I did not recall before listening to this recording.  I knew there was one of these nights I had 10th row center on the floor.  Now I recall some of the people we sat next to, the extremely loud but crystal clear keyboards during Stranger, the Althea that was a little fucked up but rocked hard nonetheless. the Aiko and the New Speedway.  I believe it was a rainy night, and apparently that was causing some short-circuiting of equipment that sounded like a Harley-Davidson was backstage during the end of the 1st set.
